Amongst the Payaguas there exists a law that if any of them dies of a disease, the phy- sician who undertook his cure shall be put to death by the arrows of the assembled people3 and being desperately addicted to revenge, they are steadfast in the execution of this cruel law. During my residence in the city of Asumpcion, an 'unhappy physician atoned sor the death of his patient by his own. Were this law in force amongst the Abipones, fewer of them would profess themselves followers of Galen3 they would shun the dangerous vprofession of medicine, and physicians would cease to grow like sunguses in a night. Of this Ι am quite sure, that in every Abiponian horde there are more physicians than sick persons: deterred by no danger of'loss of fame or life, and certain os reward, they besiege the beds of the sick, and suck away their strength in every disease.
